4.2 Few-Shot Prompting
4.2.1 Setup and Motivation
Few-shot prompting augments the zero-shot prompt with a small number of demonstration examples drawn from the training set. The objective is to condition the model on the desired output format and clinical content structure, thereby reducing the ambiguity inherent in open-ended summarization tasks. We hypothesize that few-shot examples improve output consistency and adherence to clinical documentation norms.
4.2.2 Example Selection
For each test instance, demonstration examples are selected using a stratified strategy. We include one example from the same language as the test instance (when available in the training set) to expose the model to target-language output patterns, and one example from English to provide a high-quality structural reference. This bilingual demonstration strategy is designed to balance linguistic fidelity with clinical structure quality.
The number of shots is set to k = 3, empirically balancing informativeness against context length limitations. All demonstrations are formatted as complete dialogue-summary pairs using the same prompt template as in the zero-shot condition, prepended before the target dialogue.
4.2.3 Context Window Management
Clinical dialogues can be lengthy. To ensure that all demonstrations and the target dialogue fit within the model's context window (4,096 tokens for Mistral-7B; 8,192 tokens for Qwen2.5-7B), dialogues exceeding a token threshold are truncated from the middle, preserving the opening clinical context and the closing diagnostic/treatment discussion, which carry the highest density of clinically relevant information.
4.3 Translation-Augmented Inference (IndicTrans2 Pipeline)
4.3.1 Motivation
A well-established strategy for low-resource NLP is translate-then-process: translate the source text into a high-resource language, apply the NLP pipeline in that language, and optionally back-translate the output. Given the strong English clinical summarization capabilities of both target models, we explore whether routing non-English dialogues through a high-quality neural machine translation (NMT) system before summarization yields improvements over direct multilingual inference.
4.3.2 IndicTrans2
Translation is performed using IndicTrans2, a state-of-the-art multilingual NMT model developed by AI4Bharat, specifically designed for Indian languages. IndicTrans2 supports translation between English and 22 scheduled Indian languages, covering all ten languages in our dataset. It achieves competitive BLEU scores on standard benchmarks for Indic language translation and has been shown to substantially outperform general-purpose translation systems (e.g., Google Translate) on low-resource Indian language pairs.
4.3.3 Pipeline Architecture
The translation pipeline operates as follows:
• Non-English dialogues are translated to English using IndicTrans2 (source-to-English direction).
• The translated English dialogue is passed to the summarization model (Mistral-7B or Qwen2.5-7B) using the zero-shot English prompt.
• The generated English summary is translated back to the original source language using IndicTrans2 (English-to-source direction), producing the final multilingual summary.
• English dialogues bypass the translation step entirely and are processed directly.
 
This end-to-end pipeline isolates the summarization step from cross-lingual generation challenges, allowing the model to operate in its strongest inference language (English) while delivering output in the patient's native language.
4.4 Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)
4.4.1 Motivation and Approach
Supervised fine-tuning adapts the pre-trained models directly to the target task and domain using labeled training examples. Fine-tuning allows the model to internalize the stylistic, structural, and clinical norms of the target summaries, and to develop stronger representations for low-resource languages encountered in training. We employ Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) via Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) to make training computationally feasible on 7B-parameter models.
